        <name>14.3.1.1 Volumes generated by rotating curves about the x-axis</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;h3&gt;Volumes generated by rotating curves about the x-axis&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The figure below shows a graph of the function \(y=2x\) for \(x\) between 0 and 3.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/14-3-fig-8-linegraph.svg" alt="A graph of the function y = 2x, for x between 0 and 3." width="145" height="128" class="img-responsive atto_image_button_text-bottom"&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Imagine rotating the line \(y=2x\) by one complete revolution (\(360^{\circ}\) or \(2\pi\) radians) around the \(x\)-axis. The surface so formed is the surface of a cone as shown in the figure below. Such a three-dimensional shape is known as a &lt;strong&gt;solid of revolution&lt;/strong&gt;.
    We now discuss how to obtain the volumes of such solids of revolution.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/14-3-fig-9-conerevolution.svg" alt="When line y = 2x is rotated around the axis a solid is generated. It's a cone, vertex at origin, axis = x-axis, base at x=3." width="199" height="261" class="img-responsive atto_image_button_text-bottom"&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
